{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17597936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17597936"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:30:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:30:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15433"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15433"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.32,0.05,0.24,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8124"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63684"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8124"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15433"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49123"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19698"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20883"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63684"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient presents with severe watery diarrhoea after returning from a holiday in Zimbabwe, where they did unknowingly consume contaminated water in this region where cholera is endemic.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following describes the pathophysiology of this bacterium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activation of adenylate cyclase","Blockage of chloride channels","Direct damage to intestinal cells","Inhibition of sodium-potassium pumps","Stimulation of inflammatory mediators"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EVibrio cholerae\u003C/em\u003E produces cholera toxin, which acts through a specific mechanism. It mode of action is through \u003Cstrong\u003Eactivation of adenylate cyclase\u003C/strong\u003E, leads to increased cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) levels, resulting in chloride secretion and massive fluid loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect damage to intestinal cells\u003C/strong\u003E is not the mechanism - the cells remain intact but their function is altered. \u003Cstrong\u003EStimulation of inflammatory mediators\u003C/strong\u003E is not correct as cholera causes a non-inflammatory diarrhoea. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERather than\u003Cstrong\u003E blocking of chloride channels\u003C/strong\u003E, - the cholera toxin actually increases chloride secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of sodium-potassium pumps\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - the toxin works through a different mechanism. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment focuses on aggressive fluid replacement to combat dehydration, along with appropriate antibiotics to reduce the duration of illness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cholera toxin activates adenylate cyclase leading to increased chloride secretion and water loss.","Cholera is caused by Vibrio cholerae and presents with profuse watery diarrhoea.","Treatment of cholera focuses on fluid replacement and targeted antibiotics."],"references":["Chowdhury F, Ross AG, Islam MT, McMillan NAJ, Qadri F. Diagnosis, Management, and Future Control of Cholera. Clin Microbiol Rev. 2022 Sep 21;35(3):e0021121. doi: 10.1128/cmr.00211-21. Epub 2022 Jun 21. PMID: 35726607; PMCID: PMC9491185.","Sell J, Dolan B. Common Gastrointestinal Infections. Prim Care. 2018 Sep;45(3):519-532. doi: 10.1016/j.pop.2018.05.008. Epub 2018 Jul 9. PMID: 30115338","Burd EM, Hinrichs BH. Gastrointestinal Infections. Molecular Pathology in Clinical Practice. 2015 May 19:707\u201334. doi: 10.1007/978-3-319-19674-9_50. PMCID: PMC7123654","Kotloff KL. Bacterial diarrhoea. Curr Opin Pediatr. 2022 Apr 1;34(2):147-155. doi: 10.1097/MOP.0000000000001107. PMID: 35165210","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49123"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15433"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49123"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T11:05:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T11:05:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8124"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63684"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level 